1
00:00:00,090 --> 00:00:02,940
- As soon as I left school,
I started my first business,

2
00:00:02,940 --> 00:00:04,530
which made me a multimillionaire

3
00:00:04,530 --> 00:00:06,570
and gave me the life
I'd always dreamed of.

4
00:00:06,570 --> 00:00:08,550
This statement isn't just false.

5
00:00:08,550 --> 00:00:10,200
It's pretty much impossible.

6
00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:13,350
The trouble is many people that
want to get rich are buying

7
00:00:13,350 --> 00:00:16,530
into this narrative as it's
so widespread on the internet.

8
00:00:16,530 --> 00:00:20,460
Why? Because it sounds so
much easier than the reality.

9
00:00:20,460 --> 00:00:23,190
If you wanna get rich but don't
wanna put in the hard work,

10
00:00:23,190 --> 00:00:24,960
then I'd recommend buying a lottery ticket

11
00:00:24,960 --> 00:00:26,040
and crossing your fingers

12
00:00:26,040 --> 00:00:27,720
as it'll probably be more effective.

13
00:00:27,720 --> 00:00:28,740
Don't get me wrong,

14
00:00:28,740 --> 00:00:31,920
I did make my millions from
starting successful businesses.

15
00:00:31,920 --> 00:00:32,753
However,

16
00:00:32,753 --> 00:00:34,950
I didn't just jump straight
into a business idea

17
00:00:34,950 --> 00:00:37,170
after watching a "Top
10 side hustle video."

18
00:00:37,170 --> 00:00:39,300
So when I say you have little to no chance

19
00:00:39,300 --> 00:00:42,120
of starting a successful
business straight out of school,

20
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:45,090
I'm not trying to crush your
dreams, quite the opposite.

21
00:00:45,090 --> 00:00:47,040
I want you to save your valuable time

22
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:49,770
and start building the
skillsets you need to succeed.

23
00:00:49,770 --> 00:00:51,000
So if you wanna become rich,

24
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,190
then listen up because if
I was in your position,

25
00:00:53,190 --> 00:00:54,930
I'd follow these six steps.

26
00:00:54,930 --> 00:00:57,300
Step one, find your natural talents.

27
00:00:57,300 --> 00:01:00,030
I hate the saying, "Follow your passion."

28
00:01:00,030 --> 00:01:00,870
What if your passion

29
00:01:00,870 --> 00:01:03,030
doesn't have the ability
to make you money?

30
00:01:03,030 --> 00:01:05,220
Or even worse, you just don't have one?

31
00:01:05,220 --> 00:01:08,130
It feels like one of those
overuse self-help sayings

32
00:01:08,130 --> 00:01:10,830
that doesn't actually have
any real substance around it.

33
00:01:10,830 --> 00:01:13,470
Maybe people are drawn to advice like this

34
00:01:13,470 --> 00:01:16,350
as the general population
seem obsessed with the idea

35
00:01:16,350 --> 00:01:18,570
of living a good,
balanced, and happy life.

36
00:01:18,570 --> 00:01:21,000
This, of course, is an admirable goal.

37
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:21,833
However,

38
00:01:21,833 --> 00:01:24,150
a starving artist struggles to make money

39
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:26,220
and they rarely have any of these things.

40
00:01:26,220 --> 00:01:29,400
My passion was to become
an RAF fighter pilot,

41
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:32,190
but as soon as I found
out I needed glasses,

42
00:01:32,190 --> 00:01:33,630
that dream went out the window.

43
00:01:33,630 --> 00:01:35,340
I could've continued down that path

44
00:01:35,340 --> 00:01:37,050
and wasted valuable time.

45
00:01:37,050 --> 00:01:37,883
However,

46
00:01:37,883 --> 00:01:40,740
I decided to park that
passion for later in life

47
00:01:40,740 --> 00:01:43,890
when I had enough money to
complete my pilot's license

48
00:01:43,890 --> 00:01:45,360
and fly planes for fun.

49
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:48,300
I made this choice as to be truly happy,

50
00:01:48,300 --> 00:01:51,060
I believe you first need
to fix the money issue

51
00:01:51,060 --> 00:01:52,230
as never having enough

52
00:01:52,230 --> 00:01:54,810
can lead to so many more
problems down the road.

53
00:01:54,810 --> 00:01:55,770
I can tell you this,

54
00:01:55,770 --> 00:01:58,860
the journey to making substantial
money isn't an easy one

55
00:01:58,860 --> 00:02:00,750
otherwise everyone will be doing it.

56
00:02:00,750 --> 00:02:02,190
You just have to be very honest

57
00:02:02,190 --> 00:02:03,840
about what you're actually good at.

58
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:07,320
Ray Dalio, owner of the
world's largest hedge fund,

59
00:02:07,320 --> 00:02:11,460
Bridgewater Capital, says that
you have to "Find your game,"

60
00:02:11,460 --> 00:02:12,690
and I couldn't agree more.

61
00:02:12,690 --> 00:02:15,180
I remember trying my hand at
a lot of different things,

62
00:02:15,180 --> 00:02:17,340
such as door-to-door fish sales,

63
00:02:17,340 --> 00:02:19,740
being a shop assistant, flipping cars,

64
00:02:19,740 --> 00:02:22,770
and teaching people how to
fly radio control helicopters.

65
00:02:22,770 --> 00:02:23,603
From this,

66
00:02:23,603 --> 00:02:25,890
I identified I had
natural talent for dealing

67
00:02:25,890 --> 00:02:28,650
with people due to my
strong social skills.

68
00:02:28,650 --> 00:02:29,483
From then on,

69
00:02:29,483 --> 00:02:31,380
I really leaned into anything that relied

70
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:33,840
on me speaking face-to-face with customers

71
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:35,280
as I knew I could make sales

72
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:37,140
that others could only dream of.

73
00:02:37,140 --> 00:02:39,090
Have a think about the
things that you're good at.

74
00:02:39,090 --> 00:02:41,730
And if there's a few common
skills that connect them all,

75
00:02:41,730 --> 00:02:43,200
those are your money-makers.

76
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:44,160
At this stage,

77
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:46,920
you should only be
focusing on these skills

78
00:02:46,920 --> 00:02:48,750
because it's much easier to get ahead

79
00:02:48,750 --> 00:02:52,110
improving on those rather
than starting from scratch

80
00:02:52,110 --> 00:02:53,820
with something completely new.

81
00:02:53,820 --> 00:02:56,850
You can use these natural
skills to fix your money issues

82
00:02:56,850 --> 00:02:59,880
and then from there start
improving in other areas.

83
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:02,610
Step two, dedicate everything to a job.

84
00:03:02,610 --> 00:03:05,910
I know it's become very trendy
to wanna escape the matrix.

85
00:03:05,910 --> 00:03:07,230
It's even got to the point

86
00:03:07,230 --> 00:03:09,540
where people are quietly
quitting their jobs.

87
00:03:09,540 --> 00:03:11,760
This means they're doing the bare minimum,

88
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:14,370
keeping all their energy
for their side hustles.

89
00:03:14,370 --> 00:03:16,710
Although I understand
the thinking behind this,

90
00:03:16,710 --> 00:03:18,660
doing the bare minimum is something

91
00:03:18,660 --> 00:03:20,430
that should never be celebrated.

92
00:03:20,430 --> 00:03:21,900
That is the type of mindset

93
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:24,000
that ensures you'll never be successful

94
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,130
because the way you do the small things

95
00:03:26,130 --> 00:03:27,690
is the way you'll do the big things.

96
00:03:27,690 --> 00:03:29,340
When I was working as a carpenter,

97
00:03:29,340 --> 00:03:31,320
I'd have days I just hated,

98
00:03:31,320 --> 00:03:34,260
but I knew a sour attitude
wouldn't get me anywhere.

99
00:03:34,260 --> 00:03:36,660
Even a job like this can
give you the opportunity

100
00:03:36,660 --> 00:03:38,760
to practice important skills.

101
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:42,180
I learned woodwork,
technical design, quoting,

102
00:03:42,180 --> 00:03:43,680
and customer service.

103
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:45,127
I always believed in the phrase

104
00:03:45,127 --> 00:03:47,460
"Work to learn, not to earn."
(money cha-chings)

105
00:03:47,460 --> 00:03:48,930
When I worked in a factory,

106
00:03:48,930 --> 00:03:50,280
I would always ask questions

107
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:52,260
and try to figure out how it all worked.

108
00:03:52,260 --> 00:03:55,230
This later came in very handy
when I was traveling the world

109
00:03:55,230 --> 00:03:57,960
looking for the perfect
place to manufacture

110
00:03:57,960 --> 00:04:00,900
my own products as I knew
what I was looking for.

111
00:04:00,900 --> 00:04:04,170
My experience as an assistant
in a radio control model shop

112
00:04:04,170 --> 00:04:06,870
helped me learn sales, communication,

113
00:04:06,870 --> 00:04:09,930
and organizational skills
that I'd like to train

114
00:04:09,930 --> 00:04:12,180
to my employees in my own shops.

115
00:04:12,180 --> 00:04:13,320
In your current job,

116
00:04:13,320 --> 00:04:16,110
try to understand why
things are the way they are

117
00:04:16,110 --> 00:04:18,810
without trying to argue
or question your boss.

118
00:04:18,810 --> 00:04:20,490
By looking just a little bit deeper,

119
00:04:20,490 --> 00:04:22,140
you can find there's a reason why

120
00:04:22,140 --> 00:04:24,450
pretty much everything is the way it is.

121
00:04:24,450 --> 00:04:26,040
If it's good, keep note of it.

122
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:28,470
If it's bad, also keep note of it.

123
00:04:28,470 --> 00:04:30,030
I'll explain why later.

124
00:04:30,030 --> 00:04:33,480
Step three, nurture your
contacts and your image.

125
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:35,760
These two really go hand-in-hand

126
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:37,590
because if you don't have a good image,

127
00:04:37,590 --> 00:04:39,660
then the people you want to connect with

128
00:04:39,660 --> 00:04:40,980
won't wanna be your friends.

129
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:42,270
It's harsh but true.

130
00:04:42,270 --> 00:04:44,070
We often make a quick assumption

131
00:04:44,070 --> 00:04:47,610
about a person right or wrong
after meeting them just once.

132
00:04:47,610 --> 00:04:49,620
Nowadays, due to social media,

133
00:04:49,620 --> 00:04:51,060
you don't even have to meet someone

134
00:04:51,060 --> 00:04:52,170
to have an opinion on them.

135
00:04:52,170 --> 00:04:54,060
So how you present yourself in-person

136
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:55,980
and online is very important.

137
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:58,800
I mean, think about some
of your favorite YouTubers.

138
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:01,290
They all have something
that makes them stand out.

139
00:05:01,290 --> 00:05:04,440
For me, it's me old age
and of course my wisdom.

140
00:05:04,440 --> 00:05:06,150
Take your strengths from step one,

141
00:05:06,150 --> 00:05:07,770
and try to find a way to show them off

142
00:05:07,770 --> 00:05:09,180
when you meet a new person,

143
00:05:09,180 --> 00:05:11,130
and leave an imprint in their mind.

144
00:05:11,130 --> 00:05:12,750
After failing to qualify

145
00:05:12,750 --> 00:05:16,707
for the Helicopter World
Championships in Austria in 1993

146
00:05:16,707 --> 00:05:19,500
and being absolutely devastated,

147
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:23,010
I devised a plan to make
sure that I made an impact.

148
00:05:23,010 --> 00:05:24,390
I noticed a loophole

149
00:05:24,390 --> 00:05:27,270
that would allow me to
attend as the team coach.

150
00:05:27,270 --> 00:05:28,980
Once I secured my place,

151
00:05:28,980 --> 00:05:32,220
I loaded my model helicopter
with a secret weapon.

152
00:05:32,220 --> 00:05:35,760
And after the final
competition, I executed my plan.

153
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:39,420
I flew the first ever model
helicopter firework display.

154
00:05:39,420 --> 00:05:40,560
Everyone was in awe.

155
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:43,200
The helicopter flipped,
and soared through the sky,

156
00:05:43,200 --> 00:05:46,650
followed by a glitter in trail
of sparks and explosions.

157
00:05:46,650 --> 00:05:48,660
I was featured in many newspapers

158
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:49,980
and TV shows,
(audience applauding)

159
00:05:49,980 --> 00:05:51,960
leading to me making a bigger impact

160
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:54,210
than any of the competition winners.

161
00:05:54,210 --> 00:05:56,910
I was even asked to sign
multiple autographs.

162
00:05:56,910 --> 00:05:59,310
That was before selfies were even a thing.

163
00:05:59,310 --> 00:06:00,360
Two years later,

164
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,270
I qualify for the World
Championships in Japan.

165
00:06:03,270 --> 00:06:05,460
And everyone already knew my name

166
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:07,020
from that breathtaking in night.

167
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:09,030
So you've gotta be straight with yourself.

168
00:06:09,030 --> 00:06:11,670
The world out there is too
hard for you to be soft.

169
00:06:11,670 --> 00:06:14,190
I think a better way of being
great is to go out there

170
00:06:14,190 --> 00:06:16,470
and practice the things
that will make you great.

171
00:06:16,470 --> 00:06:17,850
Rather than telling yourself

172
00:06:17,850 --> 00:06:20,070
over and over in the mirror "I'm great,"

173
00:06:20,070 --> 00:06:22,080
I'd say having proof is much better.

174
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:24,150
You don't have to be great at everything,

175
00:06:24,150 --> 00:06:27,090
but the reason most men
are so invisible nowadays

176
00:06:27,090 --> 00:06:29,010
is that they're too afraid to take risk

177
00:06:29,010 --> 00:06:30,720
for fear of standing out.

178
00:06:30,720 --> 00:06:32,760
And in this era of distraction,

179
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:35,130
social media, and quiet-quitting,

180
00:06:35,130 --> 00:06:38,190
it's easier than ever to
stand out by excelling,

181
00:06:38,190 --> 00:06:40,980
but it's also important not
to be too self-absorbed.

182
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:43,200
Most people are more
interested in themselves

183
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:44,340
than other people.

184
00:06:44,340 --> 00:06:46,650
Becoming genuinely interested in others

185
00:06:46,650 --> 00:06:49,140
can take you a long way in
business and friendships,

186
00:06:49,140 --> 00:06:51,630
even though it may seem
like a waste of time.

187
00:06:51,630 --> 00:06:54,930
Step four, identify improvements
and write them down.

188
00:06:54,930 --> 00:06:57,750
Remember how I said to write
down the stuff that was good

189
00:06:57,750 --> 00:07:00,660
and not so good about whatever
business you're working in?

190
00:07:00,660 --> 00:07:02,280
Well, here's the thing.

191
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:04,620
A lot of people who go into business do so

192
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:07,830
because the last boss they
work for was a complete idiot.

193
00:07:07,830 --> 00:07:09,600
At least that's kind
of what happened to me.

194
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:11,790
Businesses are all about solving problems,

195
00:07:11,790 --> 00:07:13,650
but the funny thing is businesses

196
00:07:13,650 --> 00:07:15,690
have tons of their own problems.

197
00:07:15,690 --> 00:07:17,190
Whenever an issue comes up

198
00:07:17,190 --> 00:07:19,530
and your boss has to
hire some outside help,

199
00:07:19,530 --> 00:07:22,470
keep a note of what the problem
was and how it was solved.

200
00:07:22,470 --> 00:07:23,820
I saw all the problems

201
00:07:23,820 --> 00:07:26,250
in the radio control model
shop I was working in,

202
00:07:26,250 --> 00:07:29,610
such as not meeting customer
demand with certain products,

203
00:07:29,610 --> 00:07:33,060
a poor location, and inexperienced staff.

204
00:07:33,060 --> 00:07:35,640
I later used this
information to start a chain

205
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:39,000
of model shops that absolutely
dominated the market.

206
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,610
This is the same idea
behind hiring a mentor

207
00:07:41,610 --> 00:07:43,260
or paying for consultants.

208
00:07:43,260 --> 00:07:44,093
However,

209
00:07:44,093 --> 00:07:45,930
this way you are actually getting paid

210
00:07:45,930 --> 00:07:47,490
while gaining the knowledge.

211
00:07:47,490 --> 00:07:50,760
Step five, test your
fixes with a side hustle.

212
00:07:50,760 --> 00:07:52,830
Starting a business is scary.

213
00:07:52,830 --> 00:07:55,710
It often means taking risk,
and putting in lots of time,

214
00:07:55,710 --> 00:07:58,800
and money up front without
any guaranteed returns.

215
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:01,920
That's why it's so important
to start with a side hustle.

216
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:04,920
Before starting my own range
of radio control models,

217
00:08:04,920 --> 00:08:07,410
I made sure to stock
everything in my shops

218
00:08:07,410 --> 00:08:10,890
to get a real handle on
what actually sold and why.

219
00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:13,860
One of my friends actually
went one step further.

220
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:16,140
He wanted to start an e-commerce store,

221
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:18,540
but couldn't afford to take any risks

222
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:20,250
as he had very limited money.

223
00:08:20,250 --> 00:08:22,710
His biggest fear was
being left with inventory

224
00:08:22,710 --> 00:08:24,150
that he just couldn't sell.

225
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:27,030
Then he had a brilliant idea.

226
00:08:27,030 --> 00:08:29,940
What if he tried to sell
a product he didn't have?

227
00:08:29,940 --> 00:08:31,260
He first tested this out

228
00:08:31,260 --> 00:08:35,250
with resistance training bands from China.

229
00:08:35,250 --> 00:08:38,130
But instead of buying them
and having them shipped over,

230
00:08:38,130 --> 00:08:39,900
he just listed them for sale.

231
00:08:39,900 --> 00:08:41,100
When the orders came in,
(messages dinging)

232
00:08:41,100 --> 00:08:43,650
it gave him proof that
the product was sellable.

233
00:08:43,650 --> 00:08:45,450
So he refunded all the orders

234
00:08:45,450 --> 00:08:46,950
and decided to buy the product

235
00:08:46,950 --> 00:08:48,860
after he knew he could sell it.

236
00:08:48,860 --> 00:08:52,350
He was able to test so many
products using this approach.

237
00:08:52,350 --> 00:08:53,820
One of the most important parts

238
00:08:53,820 --> 00:08:56,070
of the testing process is measurement.

239
00:08:56,070 --> 00:08:58,470
What gets measured gets managed.

240
00:08:58,470 --> 00:09:00,480
That's the reason why elite athletes

241
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:02,220
always measure their stats.

242
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:03,330
There's this idea now

243
00:09:03,330 --> 00:09:08,330
in startups called the
minimal viable product or MVP.

244
00:09:08,400 --> 00:09:11,610
The term was coined by the
CEO of a gaming business.

245
00:09:11,610 --> 00:09:14,430
Basically, they had the
rough idea for the game,

246
00:09:14,430 --> 00:09:17,130
but left the details on
the path of development

247
00:09:17,130 --> 00:09:19,590
largely up to the feedback of the users.

248
00:09:19,590 --> 00:09:21,270
What was once a very scrappy

249
00:09:21,270 --> 00:09:24,480
and buggy game ended up
becoming pretty amazing

250
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:26,580
by just listening to the feedback

251
00:09:26,580 --> 00:09:28,620
and making constant improvements.

252
00:09:28,620 --> 00:09:31,440
Testing your idea could be as
simple as just asking users

253
00:09:31,440 --> 00:09:34,140
what they think of it in
a Discord or a subreddit.

254
00:09:34,140 --> 00:09:35,550
It's worth remembering, though,

255
00:09:35,550 --> 00:09:37,770
the opinions of those that matter most

256
00:09:37,770 --> 00:09:39,660
are the ones that buy your product.

257
00:09:39,660 --> 00:09:41,130
And you won't know who those people are

258
00:09:41,130 --> 00:09:43,260
until you start selling on a small scale.

259
